<seg id=1> Before the end of the year, Lien Hoe might be able to redeem the remaining 65% of the bonds. </seg>
</hl>
<p>
<seg id=2> Kuala Lumpur Before the end of the year, Lien Hoe might be able to redeem the remaining 65% of the bonds or the total value of 53,810,000 ringgit bonds through loans from the bank. </seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id=3> Lien Hoe, whose annual benefit was 6%, could redeem the guarantee bonds. The total value was 85,740,000ringgit, and it's valid until 17 August 1998. </seg>
<seg id=4> Since a decline in real estate and the retrenchment of circulating capital, until the validation, Lien Hoe could only redeem 35% of the bonds. The remaining 65% of the bonds would be postponed to 17 August 2000 with the annual rate of 15%. </seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id=5> It was in last month that the Supervision Committee of the Stock Exchange approved that the validation of Lien Hoe bonds was to be postponed until 17 August 2000, and it's the first corporation in the country whose bonds had been postponed. </seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id=6> Because the market benefit dropped, Lien Hoe could redeem the remaining bonds through bank loans rather than paying 15% of the annual rate of benefit to the bondholders. </seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id=7> Chairman of the board Zeng Hualong expressed that at present the rate was low and the new financial budget plan was good for development of real estate, and Lien Hoe might be able to reverse the trend in the latter half of the year and make great progress. </seg>
</p>
